Berkshire, England","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1585–1631":"1585–1631","1577–1631":"1577–1631","1589–1640":"1589–1640","1614–1683":"1614–1683","1615–Female":"1615–Deceased","1560–1585":"1560–1585","1557–Female":"1557–Deceased","before 1577":"before 1577","Aft 1585":"after 1585","1560":"1560","18 May 1614":"18 May 1614","1557":"1557","1600":"1600","1589":"1589","1577":"1577","1631":"1631","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1640":"1640","1683":"1683","1615":"1615","1614":"1614","Broseley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Broseley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hartshorne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Shropshire): variant of   Hartshorn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hartshorn","meanings":["English: habitational name from Hartshorne (Derbyshire), from Old English <i>heort</i> ‘hart, stag’ (genitive <i>heortes</i>) + <i>horn</i> ‘horn’, perhaps in reference to the nearby hill (known as Hart Hill) and its supposed resemblance to a hart's horn. Alternatively, the name may be topographic, from Middle English <i>harteshorn</i> ‘swine cress’, for someone who lived at or near an area where swine cress grew."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705207,"age":0,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":2,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":15,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":35,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When James Hartshorne was born in 1585, in Broseley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Edward Hartshorn, was 26 and his mother, Virginia Emma Renfro, was 29. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Anne Gifford. He died in 1631, in Berkshire, England, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1585–1631":"1585–1631","1577–1631":"1577–1631","1589–1640":"1589–1640","1614–1683":"1614–1683","1615–Female":"1615–Surnud","1560–1585":"1560–1585","1557–Female":"1557–Surnud","before 1577":"enne 1577","Aft 1585":"pärast 1585","1560":"1560","18 May 1614":"18. mai 1614","1557":"1557","1600":"1600","1589":"1589","1577":"1577","1631":"1631","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1585":"1585","1640":"1640","1683":"1683","1615":"1615","1614":"1614","Broseley, Shropshire, 